Yes, I've fetched today's latest news headlines (2026-02-02) from the BBC News RSS feed and saved a structured JSON file in the project folder: `_outputs/latest_news.json`.

It includes the top 10 items with `title`, `link`, `pubDate`, and `description` for each. Example preview:

```json
{
  "news": [
    {
      "title": "Mandelson revelations raise further questions about Starmer's judgement",
      "link": "https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/ce9yekr4d9ro?at_medium=RSS&at_campaign=rss",
      "pubDate": "Mon, 02 Feb 2026 18:53:49 GMT",
      "description": "Historical revelations about Lord Mandelson would have been unlikely to have risked political damage to the prime minister directly."
    },
    // ... 9 more
  ],
  "source": "BBC News RSS",
  "fetched": "2026-02-02"
}
```

The raw XML is also saved as `_outputs/latest_news.xml`. Verified: both files exist and contain valid content (~31KB XML, ~3.7KB JSON). 

Web searches initially failed (no results for future-dated queries), so I pivoted to directly fetching/parsing a reliable RSS feed. All tasks tracked and verified via todos.
